1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,493
Many students ask VOA Learning English about studying.

2
00:00:06,493 --> 00:00:11,933
They want to know the best ways to improve their learning.

3
00:00:11,933 --> 00:00:25,747
In this week’s Education Tips, we will explore four methods you can use: focusing, testing yourself, interleaving and teaching.

4
00:00:25,747 --> 00:00:34,541
One of the best ways to organize your study session is to use the Pomodoro Technique.

5
00:00:34,541 --> 00:00:41,592
It is a powerful, but simple method that helps people focus on a task.

6
00:00:41,592 --> 00:00:44,829
The idea is to use a timer.

7
00:00:44,829 --> 00:00:53,728
Let’s say, you set the timer for 20 minutes, and focus only on your studies during that time.

8
00:00:53,728 --> 00:01:01,963
You cannot check email, send text messages or do anything aside from your task.

9
00:01:01,963 --> 00:01:11,811
When the timer goes off, you can reward yourself by listening to some music or having a drink of tea.

10
00:01:11,811 --> 00:01:17,069
You can repeat the process as many times as needed.

11
00:01:17,069 --> 00:01:31,907
If you would like to learn more details about the Pomodoro Technique, you can read a previous Education Tips story on our website, learningenglish.voanews.com

12
00:01:31,907 --> 00:01:37,029
When you are studying, you should test yourself often.

13
00:01:37,029 --> 00:01:49,224
If you are using a textbook, then you can do practice questions from the end of each chapter, as we suggested in an earlier Education Tips.

14
00:01:49,224 --> 00:01:57,125
You can also find all kinds of online tests and quizzes for many subjects.

15
00:01:57,125 --> 00:02:00,747
Flash cards are another tool.

16
00:02:00,747 --> 00:02:07,200
There are free flash card programs, or you could use pieces of paper.

17
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:15,704
The point is that you make your questions somewhat difficult, and then practice with them regularly.

18
00:02:15,704 --> 00:02:19,819
But, you should be careful about flash cards.

19
00:02:19,819 --> 00:02:25,461
Think carefully about making different kinds of questions.

20
00:02:25,461 --> 00:02:35,304
Many language learners put a vocabulary word on one side of a flash card, and the definition on the back.

21
00:02:35,304 --> 00:02:42,965
Every flash card suggests the same basic question: what does this word mean?

22
00:02:42,965 --> 00:02:56,064
While it is useful to remember what different words mean, be sure to make other kinds of questions – why questions or how questions, for example.

23
00:02:56,064 --> 00:03:07,533
So, you might ask, “Why are determiners important?” or “How can I tell the difference between the progressive tense and the simple tense?”

24
00:03:07,533 --> 00:03:12,848
When most people study, they do “blocked” practice.

25
00:03:12,848 --> 00:03:18,083
In other words, they only study one topic at a time.

26
00:03:18,083 --> 00:03:28,768
But research suggests that a different kind of practice, interleaved practice, may be better for long-term learning.

27
00:03:28,768 --> 00:03:35,389
Interleaving is a technique that means you mix different topics.

28
00:03:35,389 --> 00:03:47,691
So, for example, in one study session you might spend time testing yourself on vocabulary words and then test yourself on grammar.

29
00:03:47,691 --> 00:03:55,475
Or, if studying math, you could mix multiplication and division problems.

30
00:03:55,475 --> 00:04:08,013
A 2020 study published in the Journal of Educational Psychology found that interleaved study was much better than blocked practice.

31
00:04:08,013 --> 00:04:16,267
The study examined 54 7th grade math classes over a period of 4 months.

32
00:04:16,267 --> 00:04:24,059
Some classes did interleaved assignments while other classes did blocked assignments.

33
00:04:24,059 --> 00:04:29,021
One month later, students took a surprise test.

34
00:04:29,021 --> 00:04:42,149
The results were powerful: “The interleaved group outscored the blocked group, 61% versus 38%,” the researchers wrote.

35
00:04:42,149 --> 00:04:46,309
Teaching is also a powerful way to learn.

36
00:04:46,309 --> 00:04:55,229
In a study published in Contemporary Education Psychology, researchers compared different groups of students.

37
00:04:55,229 --> 00:05:02,315
Some students did not expect to have to teach information, while others did.

38
00:05:02,315 --> 00:05:18,885
Researchers Fiorella and Mayer wrote that when students actually teach a lesson, “they develop a deeper and more persistent understanding of the material than from solely preparing to teach.”

39
00:05:18,885 --> 00:05:27,523
In the Guardian newspaper, David Robson points out ways to teach others, even if you are alone.

40
00:05:27,523 --> 00:05:42,277
“If you don’t have a willing partner, you could imagine describing it to someone, or draft an email setting out what you’ve learned in as much detail as possible,” Robson wrote.

41
00:05:42,277 --> 00:05:48,563
You can put all of these techniques together to make a powerful study plan.

42
00:05:48,563 --> 00:05:56,197
For example, you might organize your study sessions with the Pomodoro technique.

43
00:05:56,197 --> 00:06:01,747
Then, you can test yourself and interleave different topics.

44
00:06:01,747 --> 00:06:09,275
After that, you could take a break, reward yourself and do another Pomodoro session.

45
00:06:09,275 --> 00:06:17,605
There are many options. You can create your own plan based on what you need to learn.

46
00:06:17,605 --> 00:06:28,824
But what you will realize is that when you focus and do tasks that are at the right difficulty level, your brain will become tired.

47
00:06:28,824 --> 00:06:35,827
Some days, you might only be able to do one 20-minute session, for example.

48
00:06:35,827 --> 00:06:41,221
Other days, you might do many 20-minute sessions.

49
00:06:41,221 --> 00:06:47,728
After all of that mental training, you will surely need to rest and recover.

50
00:06:47,728 --> 00:06:53,597
We will explore that topic in a future Education Tips story.

51
00:06:53,597 --> 00:06:56,456
I’m John Russell.